{
  "name": "India Open Data Explorer — Query Auth vs Header vs Bearer (Non-AI)",
  "nodes": [
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## 🇮🇳 India Open Data Explorer — Auth Mechanisms, Not AI\n\nSame webhook-and-Switch skeleton as the Gita Oracle project, but this time the lesson is different: **data.gov.in only accepts its key one way — as a URL query parameter.** Three of these six branches deliberately use the *wrong* mechanism so you can see the failure yourself, not just read about it.\n\n| # | method | Result |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `hardcoded` | ✅ works, but insecure (anti-pattern) |\n| 2 | `query_auth` | ✅ correct, hidden |\n| 3 | `header_auth` | ❌ fails — server ignores it |\n| 4 | `bearer_auth` | ❌ fails — server ignores it |\n| 5 | `code_query` | ✅ correct, built in JS |\n| 6 | `config_abstraction` | ✅ correct, config-driven |\n\n**Before running:** replace `YOUR_RESOURCE_ID` in every HTTP node with a real dataset ID from data.gov.in's catalog (search \"population\" or \"census\" on data.gov.in, open any dataset's API page, copy the ID from the sample URL).",
        "height": 460,
        "width": 620,
        "color": 5
      },
      "id": "sticky-overview-in01",
      "name": "📖 Project Overview",
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [-1300, -520]
    },
